snippet.title: Paleontologists discover 'chicken from hell' dinosaur
snippet.description: Scientists from the Carnegie and Smithsonian museums, as well as the University of Utah, have unveiled a new dinosaur they have dubbed the "chicken from hell."

snippet.title: Dramatic dinosaur chase scene reconstructed from old photos
snippet.description: Over 110 million years ago, a compelling scene played out between two dinosaurs. A digital reconstruction tells the story.

snippet.title: For Pleo the robot dinosaur, a second act in an American life
snippet.description: In 2007 and 2008, the cute and cuddly Pleo was a huge hit. Then its maker went out of business, and the dinosaur disappeared from view. So what is it doing at CES 2014?

snippet.title: Record dinosaur tail unearthed in Mexico
snippet.description: Paleontologists in the northern Mexican state of Coahuila reveal a 16-foot dinosaur tail with 50 connected vertebrae intact.

snippet.title: Rare dinosaur tail uncovered (pictures)
snippet.description: See detailed images of an amazing find: a 16-foot dinosaur tail buried for up to 72 million years. Fifty connected vertebrae remain intact.

snippet.title: Scientists run dinosaur wind-tunnel tests
snippet.description: Researchers looking into the evolution of bird flight take a Microraptor model into a wind tunnel for answers.

snippet.title: A brand-new dinosaur noses its way into the books
snippet.description: With its prominent proboscis, this newly announced species of dinosaur isn't quite like the Triceratops you remember from those school field trips to the museum.

snippet.title: Mozilla names insider Chris Beard as interim CEO
snippet.description: Trying to recover quickly from a firestorm over gay marriage that brought down its last CEO in just 11 days, Mozilla names a new chief executive and begins to reshape its board.

snippet.title: Microsoft names Satya Nadella as CEO
snippet.description: Microsoft didn't have to look far in its six-month search for a new CEO. The company has tapped Satya Nadella to replace Steve Ballmer. Nadella, who has been at Microsoft for 22 years, will become the third CEO in Microsoft's four-decade-long history. As CNET's Kara Tsuboi reports, Microsoft's new chief faces some serious challenges.

snippet.title: New domain names, same old trademark problems
snippet.description: As Net addresses like .pink, .flights, and .coffee arrive, trademark holders have some new versions of old headaches. Canyon Bicycle prevailed to claim canyon.bike, though.
